                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2003-09-30</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Every discipline has key introductory texts that motivate the subject, whet the appetite for more, and guide a novice to see the forest despite the trees.  'Combinatorics' by Peter Cameron is one such gem!  Combinatorics has a reputation for being a collection of disparate clever ad hoc arguments.  The author has carefully presented binding principles such as double counting, the pigeon-hole principle, generating functions, enumeration via group actions, sets of  distinct representatives,...see the book for more, that makes coherent combinatorics as a discourse, despite its diverse application.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Best Single Book on Combinatorics</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
